#: ../../../development/abi.md:1
msgid "The PyEmscripten Platform"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:5
msgid "What is the PyEmscripten Platform?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:7
msgid ""
"The PyEmscripten platform defines a binary interface for an Emscripten "
"application. If an Emscripten application and an Emscripten shared library "
"are both built to target this platform, then the application will be able to "
"load and run the shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:12
msgid ""
"To build a shared library that is compatible with a given version of "
"Pyodide, it is necessary to identify which PyEmscripten platform that "
"version of Pyodide uses and follow the corresponding shared library build "
"instructions. This allows wheels to be built for Pyodide that will load and "
"run correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:17
msgid ""
"The Emscripten compiler makes no ABI stability guarantees between versions, "
"and several linker flags can adjust the ABI. Therefore, Python packages "
"built for Emscripten must match the ABI-sensitive compiler and linker flags "
"used to build the interpreter to avoid load-time or run-time errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:22
msgid ""
"To balance ABI stability needs of package maintainers with flexibility to "
"adopt new platform features and bug fixes, Pyodide adopts a new PyEmscripten "
"platform for each feature release of Python. The platform tags take the form "
"`pyemscripten_${YEAR}_${PATCH}_wasm32` (e.g., `pyemscripten_2026_0_wasm32` "
"for Python 3.14). Prior to Python 3.14, it was called the Pyodide platform "
"instead of the PyEmscripten platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:29
msgid "Each PyEmscripten platform specifies:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:31
msgid "the version of the Emscripten compiler to be used,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:32
msgid "what libraries are statically linked to the application,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:33
msgid "the stack unwinding ABI to be used,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:34
msgid "how the loader handles dependency lookup, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:35
msgid "various additional compile and linker flags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:37
msgid ""
"The PyEmscripten platform definition does not include anything about Python "
"and in particular it is agnostic to the Python version it is intended to be "
"used with. However, for clarity we indicate in the platform documentation "
"which Python version we plan to use each platform with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:42
msgid ""
"The PyEmscripten platform is part of a draft Python packaging specification. "
"See [PEP 783](https://peps.python.org/pep-0783/) for the full specification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:45
msgid "Platform Versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:47
msgid "[pyemscripten_2026_0](abi/314.md) (Python 3.14, under development)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:48
msgid "[pyodide_2025_0](abi/313.md) (Python 3.13)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:49
msgid "[pyodide_2024_0](abi/312.md) (Python 3.12)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:51
msgid ""
"For background on why specific flags were chosen, see [ABI-sensitive flags]"
"(abi/flags.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:63
msgid "General"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:65
msgid "Building for the Emscripten target"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:67
msgid "To build C/C++ projects, use the Emscripten compiler toolchain `emcc`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:69
msgid ""
"To build Rust projects, use `rustc --target wasm32-unknown-emscripten` or "
"`cargo build --target wasm32-unknown-emscripten`. When building, `emcc` must "
"be on the path or linking will fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:73
msgid "Making a shared library"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:75
msgid ""
"Emscripten shared libraries use the [the WebAssembly binary format](https://"
"webassembly.github.io/spec/core/binary/index.html) and have a [dynamic "
"linking section](https://github.com/WebAssembly/tool-conventions/blob/main/"
"DynamicLinking.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:79
msgid ""
"`emcc` will ignore the `-shared` flag. To make a shared library with `emcc`, "
"you must pass `-sSIDE_MODULE=1` or `-sSIDE_MODULE=2`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:82
msgid ""
"With Rust version 1.95.0 and later, Rust will automatically detect that the "
"crate is a cdylib and link an Emscripten shared library. For older Rust "
"versions, to make a shared library with `rustc`, pass `-C link-arg=-"
"sSIDE_MODULE=2`. To build a shared library with `cargo`, put `-C link-arg=-"
"sSIDE_MODULE=2` in the `RUSTFLAGS` environment variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:88
msgid "Static Libraries Linked to the Main Binary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:90
msgid ""
"Many libraries cannot be dynamically linked on the Emscripten platform, most "
"frequently because they contain JavaScript code. If they are to be made "
"available for packages to use, they must be statically linked to the "
"interpreter. There are also a few libraries that are needed for a Python "
"builtin module. As a part of the platform definition, we document which "
"versions of which libraries are linked to the main binary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:97
msgid "Other Library Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:99
msgid ""
"Other library dependencies should either be statically linked to the "
"extension module or built as a shared library and vendored into the wheel in "
"a `.libs` directory. Like on native platforms, the RPATH of the dependent "
"extension module should also be set as appropriate to ensure that the "
"dependency is resolved correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:105
msgid "No pthreads support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:107
msgid ""
"`-pthread` must not be used at compile or link time. If `-pthread` is used, "
"the resulting libraries will not load."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:110
msgid "Controlling the Set of Exported Symbols"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:112
msgid ""
"All symbols that form part of a binary module's interface must be exported. "
"It is desirable to produce the minimal list of exported symbols to keep "
"download size and runtime to a minimum. Not exporting symbols also reduces "
"chances of symbol collisions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:117
msgid ""
"Linking a shared libraries with `-sSIDE_MODULE=1` will pass `-whole-archive` "
"to `wasm-ld` and so force inclusion of all object files and all symbols. "
"Linking with `-sSIDE_MODULE=2` will only include symbols that are explicitly "
"listed with `-sEXPORTED_FUNCTIONS=<export list>`. The name of each symbol in "
"the list must be prefixed with an underscore. For the smallest result, it is "
"recommended to link with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../development/abi.md:124
msgid ""
"-sSIDE_MODULE=2 -sEXPORTED_FUNCTIONS=[\"_PyInit_MyCModule1\", "
"\"_PyInit_MyCModule2]\n"
msgstr ""
